What is R ?

  • Open source statistical programming language.
    • A collaborative effort
    • many people contribute
  • to include a package first we need to install the package
  install.packages("package-name")
  library("package-name")
  • Install the package only once, but you have to include it every time you start R
  • You want to contribute? Build a package and upload it to Comprehensive R Archive Network, CRAN
  • Its free, it runs on Windows-MAC-Linux/Unix

Install R and RStudio

  • Get R from http://cran.r-project.org/
  • Install a typesetting software latex or Miktex from http://miktex.org/download
    • for MAC user it would be MacTex
  • Get RStudio desktop version from http://www.rstudio.com/
    • RStuio provides convenient environment.
  • Its all free
  • Please make sure you install them in the sequence mentioned above

Modes of data in R

  • numeric
  • character
  • logical
  • factor
  • ordered
  • complex
  • raw
  • NULL

How do you get the mode?

mode(5+3i)
## [1] "complex"

Checking and changing the mode

x <- "5.42"
is.numeric(x)
## [1] FALSE
y <- as.numeric("5.44")
mode(y)
## [1] "numeric"
is.logical(FALSE)
## [1] TRUE

Organizing data

  • Can we always plot the data without reorganizing it?
  • There are three types of reorganizations
    • tidy data
    • reshape the data
    • transform the data
  • When data is received, the first step is to check if it violates the basic principles of tidy data.
  • Reshaping the data is needed when we want to map the variable to an aesthetic but variable is not explicitly available
  • Transforming is needed when some theoretical/ mathematical model is fitted or associated with the data

Plotting Tidy data

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(tidyDat, aes(x = type, y = calls, color = department, fill = department)) + 
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.4)

Wide vs long form data

Let us do it

  • Read the wide form data
wdat <- read.csv("https://mamajumder.github.io/data-science/data/wdat.csv")
  • Load the package and convert to long form
library(reshape2)
mdat <- melt(wdat, id = "year")
mdat
##   year    variable value
## 1 2010 online.sale    20
## 2 2011 online.sale    24
## 3 2012 online.sale    35
## 4 2010  store.sale    25
## 5 2011  store.sale    31
## 6 2012  store.sale    40

Let us do it

  • Now plot the long form data
ggplot(mdat, aes(x=year, y=value, color = variable)) +
  geom_line()

Aggregating data

Let us aggregate data

library(dplyr)
avgSales <- mdat %>% 
  group_by(variable) %>%
  summarise( avegrage.sales = mean(value))
kable(avgSales, format = "html", table.attr = "style='width:30%;'")
variable avegrage.sales
online.sale 26.33333
store.sale 32.00000
